mods:mods.abstract: Photograph of a fundraiser for Don Anderson, an injured student. The person wearing a formal suit is identified as Florida State University Vice President Dr. A. B. Martin who is making a donation to aid with the medical expenses of the student. The signs on the photographs read "Don's Wishing Well" and "Will your wish come true? Wishing well."

mods:mods.note: "In the fresh-water marshes of the Everglades, the southern or "you all" branch of the big Florida snail family is found. Drainage projects have turned the large mollusk out of much of his former habitat. As a result the snail is disappearing and so is the rare Everglade kite, a bird that eats nothing except this particular snail." This photograph was used in an article that Mary Lou Norwood wrote for publication.

titleInfo.title: Man with Empty Shells of the Pomacea

originInfo.publisher: Heritage Protocol, Florida State University, Tallahassee, Florida.

mods:mods.note: "The numerous empty shells of the Pomacea found in Indian middens seem to indicate that these snails were an important item in the Indian diet. These shells are from an Indian mound near the St. Johns River." Writting on the back of the photograph indicates that the shells were found at Little Lake George, Putnam County. This photograph was used in an article that Mary Lou Norwood wrote for publication.
